* Categories of Annotations

1. Marker Annotations
   ➡  These annotations contain no members, attributes, etc.
   ➡ @Override is an example of Marker Annotation_01.

2. Single value Annotations
   ➡ These annotations contain only one member and allow a shorthand form
     of specifying the value of the member.
   ➡ Example :- @TestAnnotation(“testing”);

3. Full Annotations
   ➡ These annotations consist of multiple data members, names, values, pairs.
   ➡ Example:- @TestAnnotation(owner=”Rahul”, value=”Class Geeks”)

4. Type Annotations
   ➡ These annotations can be applied to any place where a type is being used.
   ➡ These are declared annotated with @Target annotation.

5. Repeating Annotations
   ➡ These are the annotations that can be applied to a single item more than once.
   ➡ For repeatable annotation @Repeatable, it defined in the java.lang.annotation package.

   * In Java, when you use an annotation multiple times on the same thing, Java needs a way to store all those annotations together.
     That "storage" is what we call the container

   Example:-

   @Game("Cricket")                                         @Games({
   @Game("Football")        Here @Game is repeatable.          @Game("Cricket"),
   @Game("Hockey")        ➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡➡        @Game("Football"),
   class Sports {}                                             @Game("Hockey")
                                                            })
                                                            class Sports {}

* So the container (@Games) is just an annotation that holds an array of the repeatable annotation (@Game).